<h1 id="introduction">Introduction</h1>

<h2 id="von-neuman-bottleneck">von Neuman Bottleneck</h2>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>The von Neumann architecture is a hardware architecture.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>von Neumann architecture uses a single bus for both, code and data.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>This architecture gives rise to something called the von Neumann Bottleneck.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>The problem is that code cannot execute while data is being transferred.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Other hardware architectures repair this problem by using multiple buses.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Other architectures allow asynchronous (at the same time) transfer of data and code.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<h2 id="can-programming-be-liberated">Can Programming Be Liberated‚Ä¶</h2>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>famous paper ‚ÄúCan programming be liberated from the von Neumann style?: a functional style and its algebra of programs‚Äù<sup id="fnref:fn1" role="doc-noteref"><a href="#fn:fn1" class="footnote">1</a></sup></p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>proposes the idea that the von Neumann hardware architecture translates directly into the software domain</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<h2 id="algol-bottleneck">ALGOL Bottleneck</h2>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Software has yet another bottleneck that doesn‚Äôt involve the underlying hardware</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>I call this the ALGOL Bottleneck</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Lack of asynchrony</p>
  </li>
</ul>

